0":"1270","1292":"1292","about 1296":"about 1296","Pencarreg, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Pencarreg, Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Philip","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names ¬© Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Varughese, Mathai, Babu, Reji, Anil, Binu, Neena, Prema, Raju, Reena, Susheela, Aleykutty.","Scottish, English, German, Dutch, and Jewish: from the Greek personal name <i>Philippos</i> (from <i>philein</i> ‚Äėto love‚Äô + <i>hippos</i> ‚Äėhorse‚Äô). In the New Testament this name is borne by one of the apostles; it was also borne by various other early Christian saints. It owes part of its popularity to the medieval romances about Alexander the Great, whose father was Philip of Macedon. As a Jewish name, it represents a borrowing of the personal name from Christians. As a Highland Scottish surname, it represents an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‚Äėson of Philip‚Äô. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Spanish   Felipe  , Catalan <b>Felip</b>, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian or Croatian   Filip  , Albanian   Filipi  , and their derivatives (see examples at   Philips  ). The name <i>Philip</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Philipose   and   Pothen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Phillip  .","French (southern) and Breton (Finist√®re): variant of   Philippe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McKillip","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‚Äėson of Philip‚Äô (see   Philip  ). See also   McPhillips  ."]},{"name":"Felipe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Juana, Miguel, Orlando, Pedro, Angel, Carlos, Emilio, Jesus.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Felipe</i>, an equivalent of   Philippe  ."]},{"name":"Lips","meanings":["North German, Flemish, and Dutch: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Philips</i>, from Latin <i>Philippus</i> (see   Philip  )."]},{"name":"Lipps","meanings":["North German: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Philipps</i>, from Latin <i>Philippus</i> (see   Philip  )."]},{"name":"Pepin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Camille, Emile, Pierre, Gilles, Lucien, Normand, Alcide, Fernand, Jacques, Marcel.","French (<b>P√©pin</b>) and English: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Pipin</i>, of uncertain, probably onomatopoeic origin. The name was borne by several Frankish kings, most notably Pepin le Bref, father of Charlemagne, and remained popular throughout the early Middle Ages.","English: from the unrecorded Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal names <i>Pipin</i>, <i>Pepin</i>, <i>Pipun</i>, pet forms of   Philip  . Compare   Pipe  ."]},{"name":"Lippens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alfons, Alphons.  French Andre.","Flemish and Dutch: patronymic from a shortened form of the personal name   Philip  ."]},{"name":"Philbin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Philb√≠n</b>, ‚Äėson of Philbin (Irish <i>Philb√≠n</i> or <i>Filib√≠n</i>)‚Äô, a pet form of   Philip  ."]},{"name":"Lipman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Mayer, Chaim, Dov, Isadore, Jakob, Meyer, Pinchas.","Dutch: habitational name from a farm named Lipman or perhaps Lippink, referring to a certain <i>Lippo</i> and his kin. <i>Lippo</i> is a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name composed with the element <i>leiba</i> ‚Äėoffspring, son‚Äô, or of the personal name   Philip  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish personal name <i>Lipman</i>, derived from Middle High German words <i>liep</i> ‚Äėdear, beloved‚Äô + <i>man</i> ‚Äėman‚Äô."]},{"name":"Philipose","meanings":["Indian (Kerala): from the personal name <i>Philipose</i>, derived from Greek <i>Philippos</i> (see   Philip  ), found among Christians in southern India. ‚ÄĒ Note: Since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, this name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Philibert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Fernand, Mirielle, Pascale, Pierrot.","French: from the personal name <i>Philibert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Filuberht</i>, composed of the elements <i>fila</i> ‚Äėmuch, very‚Äô + <i>berht</i> ‚Äėbright‚Äô, which was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, abbot of Jumi√®ges. The spelling has been influenced by personal names of Greek origin based on <i>philein</i> ‚Äėto love‚Äô, e.g.   Philip  ."]}]},{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names ¬© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]},{"name":"Blaene","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names ¬© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Bl√°√°n</i>, originally a byname, a diminutive form of <i>bl√°</i> ‚Äėyellow‚Äô. This was the name of an early Celtic saint who lived in the 6th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Blain","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Bl√°√°n</i>, originally a byname, a diminutive form of <i>bl√°</i> ‚Äėyellow‚Äô. This was the name of an early Celtic saint who lived in the 6th century."]},{"name":"Blane","meanings":["Variant spelling of  